                                <p> By Jon Cox</p>
                                <p> ZURICH, Sept 23 (Reuters) - Switzerland has a problem any  other state would be only too happy to grapple with: what to do  with a $10 billion plus windfall from gold sales?</p>
                                <p> But Swiss voters failed to decide at the weekend what to do  with the cash pile, originally intended for the needy at home or  abroad.</p>
                                <p> Now, they might cut taxes instead.</p>
                                <p> "It's really completely open," said Daniel Eckmann,  spokesman for the federal finance ministry, following voters'  rejection of plans to shore up the AHV state pension scheme.</p>
                                <p> Options now being floated include slashing national debt,  giving the money to regional and national governments, providing  tax breaks for families, financing an innovation fund for the  Alpine state's economy, or revisiting aid to state pensions.</p>
                                <p> The Swiss National Bank started in May 2000 to sell just  over half its 2,590 tonnes of gold -- by far the biggest  reserves in the world per capita -- which could eventually reach  some 19 billion Swiss francs ($12.8 billion).</p>
                                <p> Part of the money was originally seen helping the needy and  stemmed from a 1997 idea for a Solidarity Foundation to counter  accusations that the Swiss were cold-blooded profiteers during  World War Two.</p>
                                <p> But this was largely superseded as Swiss banks later set up  a $1.25 billion fund to settle class-action lawsuits over  accusations they stole money from Holocaust victims. Other Swiss  firms also contributed funds for needy victims.</p>
                                <p> Even though Berne made clear the foundation would not pay  compensation to any individual Holocaust victims, many Swiss  still associated it with Jewish causes.</p>
                                <p> Berne's plan was for annual interest income -- perhaps one  billion Swiss francs -- to be divided between the fund, regional  governments and AHV. A humanitarian fund was now off the agenda,  Swiss President Kasper Villiger said. </p>
                                <p> A proposal for all of the interest income to go to the AHV  was also rejected by voters over the weekend.</p>
                                <p> While all of the money could be used in one go, the federal  government still favoured using only interest income.</p>
                                <p> "The Federal Council said it would be wise not to spend it  all but to keep it as a reserve. But theoretically everything is  possible," said Eckmann.</p>
                                <p> "Rough analysis tells us that two-thirds of the people or  even more say they want to give something to the elderly," said  Eckmann. "We don't think we will find a completely different  idea but you just don't know," he added.</p>
                                <p> No concrete proposal is seen until 2003 at the earliest.  Change in the consensus-based Swiss political model is glacial.  The main four political parties have to make proposals and these  will be reviewed by the government as will the vote.    </p>
